[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Ellicott's Commentary for English Readers",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(7) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "A devout soldier.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "—The word implies that the man was, like his superior officer, a convert to the faith of Israel, though not, in the full sense of the word, a proselyte. It is natural to infer the same of the two slaves to whom their master imparted the vision, which to those who were living as heathens would have seemed strange and unintelligible. It is obvious that all such facts are interesting as throwing light on the character of Cornelius, and showing that, to the extent of his power, he sought to lead those over whom he had any influence to the Truth which he had found precious as leading him to a higher life.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Acts 10:7-8",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 10:7-8",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "When the angel was departed, he called, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "&c. — He was obedient to the heavenly vision, without dispute or delay, and sent forthwith to Joppa to fetch Peter to him. Had he himself only been concerned, he might have gone to Joppa to Peter; but he had a family, and kinsmen and friends, (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 10:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ",) a little congregation of them, that could not go with him, and therefore he sends for Peter. And to show him the greater respect, he sends ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "two of his household servants ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— All of whom feared God; (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 10:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ";) ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and a devout soldier that waited on him continually",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " — Always attended his person. How many such attendants have our modern officers? A devout soldier would now be looked upon by many as little better than a deserter from his colours. Observe, a devout centurion had devout soldiers; a little devotion, indeed, commonly goes a great way with soldiers; but there would be more of it in them, if there were more of it in their commanders. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "And when he had declared all these things ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Just in the manner they had happened, of which he informed them, because Peter’s coming was a matter in which they also were concerned, having souls to save as well as he. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "He sent them to Joppa ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— That very evening. Thus, on Cornelius’s part, all things are disposed toward his receiving the gospel; and the same providence, at the same time, disposes all things on Peter’s part toward his coming to publish it.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Matthew Henry's Concise Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "10:1-8 Hitherto none had been baptized into the Christian church but Jews, Samaritans, and those converts who had been circumcised and observed the ceremonial law; but now the Gentiles were to be called to partake all the privileges of God's people, without first becoming Jews. Pure and undefiled religion is sometimes found where we least expect it. Wherever the fear of God rules in the heart, it will appear both in works of charity and of piety, neither will excuse from the other. Doubtless Cornelius had true faith in God's word, as far as he understood it, though not as yet clear faith in Christ. This was the work of the Spirit of God, through the mediation of Jesus, even before Cornelius knew him, as is the case with us all when we, who before were dead in sin, are made alive. Through Christ also his prayers and alms were accepted, which otherwise would have been rejected. Without dispute or delay Cornelius was obedient to the heavenly vision. In the affairs of our souls, let us not lose time.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Barnes' Notes on the Bible",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "A devout soldier - A pious man. This is an instance of the effect of piety in a military officer. Few people have more influence; and in this case the effect was seen not only in the piety of his family, but of this attending soldier. Such men have usually been supposed to be far from the influence of religion; but this instance shows that even the disadvantages of a camp are not necessarily hostile to the existence of piety. Compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 3:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "7, 8. when the angel … was departed, he called—immediately doing as directed, and thereby showing the simplicity of his faith.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "a devout soldier of them that waited on him continually—of the \"soldiers under him,\" such as the centurion at Capernaum had (Mt 8:9). Who this \"devout soldier\" was, can only be matter of conjecture. Da Costa [Four Witnesses] gives a number of ingenious reasons for thinking that, having attached himself henceforth to Peter—whose influence in the composition of the second Gospel is attested by the earliest tradition, and is stamped on that Gospel itself—he is no other than the Evangelist Mark.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
